ce:section.ce:para:
To study on the effect of His-GQD-HAD on the upconversion fluorescence emission, photoluminescence (PL) spectra of three NaYF4:Yb,Er-based upconversion materials upon illumination with 980 nm laser were measured. Fig. 3
                         indicates that all upconversion materials exhibit a very similar PL emission spectrum, which is one characteristic upconversion fluorescence spectrum from Yb and Er-doped NaYF4 crystals (shown in Fig. 4
                        ). The result proves that the introduction of His-GQD-HDA doesn’t change the energy levels of NaYF4:Yb,Er crystals. In the PL emission spectrum, the blue emissions at 411 nm is corresponded to the transition from 2H9/2 to 4I15/2, the green emission at 532 and 542 nm is assigned to the transitions from 2H11/2 to 4I15/2 and from 4S3/2 to 4I15/2, and the red emission at 655 nm is due to the transition form 4F9/2 to 4I15/2. However, we can see that the as-synthesized His-GQD-HDA-NaYF4:Yb,Er exhibits the strongest PL emission among three upconversion materials. To evaluate the emission efficiencies of different materials, the fluorescence quantum yields of three materials were measured and calculated by using one reported method [35]. The quantum yield of His-GQD-HDA-NaYF4:Yb,Er reaches to 1.49%, which is higher than that of most upconversion materials in Table s1. The value is also more than 30.5-fold that of the oil-soluble NaYF4:Yb,Er prepared by classical solovthermal method [36] and 78.3-fold that of the water-soluble NaYF4:Yb,Er made via classical hydrothermal method [37]. This confirms that the hybrid of His-GQD-HDA and NaYF4:Yb,Er achieves to a significant enhancement of upconverision emission. To understand the enhancement mechanism, the absorption and PL emission spectrum of His-GQD-HAD are studied in visible and NIR regions and the results were shown in Fig. s3. A high absorption peak at 342 nm and a broad absorption band one staring at 900 nm appear in the UV–vis-NIR absorption spectrum of His-GQD-HAD in Fig. s3A. Fig. s3B and C indicate that the His-GQD-HDA gives one strong visible fluorescence emission peak at 416 nm under the ultraviolet light exciation with the wavelength of 342 nm, and one NIR fluoresence emission band located at 1100 nm under the NIR light exciation with the wavelength of 980 nm. The results prove that the His-GQD-HDA has the ability to absorb and emit NIR light. The characteristic makes it plays an antenna if it is in close vicinity with NaYF4:Yb,Er crystals, transferring the quanta to NaYF4:Yb,Er crystals [38]. Compared with single NaYF4:Yb,Er crystals, the His-GQD-HDA-NaYF4:Yb,Er hybrid can collect more photons and results in a significant enhancement of upconversion emission. For the sake of comparison, the enhancement factors caused by different methods are given in Table s2. Table s2 indicates that the His-GQD-HDA-NaYF4:Yb,Er hybrid offers the biggest enhancement factor compared with the other methods in Table s2. We suggest that a significant enhancement is attibuted to unique structure of His-GQD-HAD-NaYF4:Yb,Er hybrid. On the one hand, the His-GQD-HDA is linked to the surface of NaYF4:Yb,Er crystals via NRE bond. The distance between His-GQD-HDA and NaYF4:Yb,Er crystal is the length of one NRE bond, which is obviously less than that of the other methods in Table s2. A reduce of the distance greatly improves the efficiency of energy transfer and leads to a more enhancement of upconverision emission. On the other hand, the as-synthesized NaYF4:Yb,Er crystals have a small particle size. The small particle size of NaYF4:Yb,Er crystals makes more Yb3+ ions can be exposed to the outside. The exposed Yb3+ ions combine with the graphene sheets to produce more antennas for collecting photons. The increase of the number of the antennas brings more energy transfer between His-GQD-HAD and NaYF4:Yb,Er, resulting in a more enhancement of upconversion enhancement.
